kflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Slot A: \"two instances of the runner start at the same time\" and each migration is applied exactly once. Slot B: Failure boundary is cross-process concurrency (real process scheduling/locking timing). Slot C: Integration in one process with mocks/fakes cannot reproduce race windows between separate processes. Rejection-gate: Integration rejected by explicit text \"two instances... at the same time\" which requires real subprocess-level contention.","test_description":"Launch two real runner processes simultaneously against the same Postgres DB and same migration set; wait for both exits; assert migration effects are present exactly once and `_migrations` has one record per migration with no duplicates. Repeat multiple times to catch race conditions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Real concurrent processes are required; lower levels cannot faithfully expose inter-process races.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"first run... `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.\" Slot B: Failure boundary is bootstrap schema creation + migration apply sequencing across components. Slot C: Unit tests for \"create table if not exists\" miss ordering bugs where first migration runs before metadata init. Integration-brake: (a) no required real OS/network/subprocess behavior, (b) no AI/ML, (c) no multi-agentic chain, (d) no LLM orchestration. Rejection-gate: System rejected because behavior text concerns startup order in DB workflow, not subprocess/